    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nPython historically has represented `0` as a longobject with `size == 0` (though I learned while tracking this bug down that this changed recently, and that's related to how this bug got introduced). The code for `&` references `digits` even when `size == 0`: https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/master/Cython/Utility/Optimize.c#L1212-L1218. \r\n\r\nThis was fine for the \"canonical\" 0 produced by the small int optimization, which always allocates one digit, but historically at least it has been possible to produce `0`s that *aren't* canonical. On Python 3.10 and earlier, `int.from_bytes` does not apply the small int optimization (https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/90519), and allocates a `0` entry `digits` array. \r\n\r\nThis means that on Python 3.10 and earlier, `&` can dereference random memory.\r\n\r\nI *think* the issue was introduced in GH-5353, which removed the check\r\nagainst `size` in response to changes in PyLong's representation.\r\n(Well, or in one of the follow ups dealing with problems that caused: 4c5f1b4b36, 6d6d49d2d6.)\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n```cython\r\ndef asdf():\r\n    z = int.from_bytes(b'\\x00', 'big')\r\n    print(z & 0xff)\r\n\r\n\r\nasdf()\r\n```\r\n\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nIt should print `0`. It actually prints other numbers. I've seen `16` and `24`, and I think maybe some others.\n\n### OS\n\nLinux\n\n### Python version\n\n3.10 and earlier\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.0.11\n\n### Additional context\n\nI'm preparing a PR to fix this by moving this `&` optimization after the zero check.",
